# ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
#  Midnight Glass Plymouth script — generated from theme.toml
# ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Window.SetBackgroundTopColor({{ colors.bg0 | rgb_float }});
Window.SetBackgroundBottomColor({{ colors.bg1 | rgb_float }});

screen_width = Window.GetWidth();
screen_height = Window.GetHeight();

# 0 = boot splash mode, 1 = password dialog active (hides splash so prompt is readable)
global.dialog_active = 0;

# ── Title text ──────────────────────────────────
title_image = Image.Text("{{ plymouth.logo_text }}", {{ colors.fg | rgb_float }}, 1, "Sans Bold 36");
title_sprite = Sprite(title_image);
title_sprite.SetX(screen_width / 2 - title_image.GetWidth() / 2);
title_sprite.SetY(screen_height / 2 - title_image.GetHeight() / 2 - 40);

subtitle_image = Image.Text("{{ plymouth.title }}", {{ colors[plymouth.pulse_color] | rgb_float }}, 0.85, "Sans 14");
subtitle_sprite = Sprite(subtitle_image);
subtitle_sprite.SetX(screen_width / 2 - subtitle_image.GetWidth() / 2);
subtitle_sprite.SetY(screen_height / 2 - subtitle_image.GetHeight() / 2 + 20);

# ── Pulsing indicator ──────────────────────────
progress = 0;

fun refresh_callback() {
    # Freeze the pulse when a password dialog is up, so it doesn't look
    # like the system is still booting while waiting for input.
    if (global.dialog_active) {
        return;
    }
    progress = progress + 0.04;
    phase = Math.Sin(progress);
    alpha = (phase + 1) / 2 * 0.7 + 0.3;
    subtitle_sprite.SetOpacity(alpha);
}

Plymouth.SetRefreshFunction(refresh_callback);

# ── Progress bar (boot progress) ──────────────
bar_width = 200;
bar_height = 2;

fun boot_progress_callback(duration, progress) {
    # Draw a thin progress line under the subtitle
    return 0;
}

Plymouth.SetBootProgressFunction(boot_progress_callback);

# ── Password prompt (for encrypted disks) ─────
# NOTE: sprite refs MUST live in global scope. Plymouth releases sprites whose
# script-side references go out of scope, so storing them in a function-local
# `dialog.foo` hash makes them vanish the instant the callback returns — the
# classic symptom is that the splash hides but no password UI ever appears.
fun display_password_callback(prompt, bullets) {
    global.dialog_active = 1;
    title_sprite.SetOpacity(0);
    subtitle_sprite.SetOpacity(0);

    # Force a clear prompt label if systemd didn't supply one.
    if (!prompt) {
        prompt = "Enter passphrase:";
    }
    global.prompt_image = Image.Text(prompt, {{ colors.fg | rgb_float }}, 1, "Sans 16");
    global.prompt_sprite = Sprite(global.prompt_image);
    global.prompt_sprite.SetPosition(
        screen_width / 2 - global.prompt_image.GetWidth() / 2,
        screen_height / 2 - 20,
        100);

    dots = "";
    for (i = 0; i < bullets; i++) {
        dots = dots + "●";
    }
    global.dots_image = Image.Text(dots, {{ colors[plymouth.pulse_color] | rgb_float }}, 1, "Sans 18");
    global.dots_sprite = Sprite(global.dots_image);
    global.dots_sprite.SetPosition(
        screen_width / 2 - global.dots_image.GetWidth() / 2,
        screen_height / 2 + 16,
        100);
}

Plymouth.SetDisplayPasswordFunction(display_password_callback);

fun display_normal_callback() {
    if (global.prompt_sprite) {
        global.prompt_sprite.SetOpacity(0);
    }
    if (global.dots_sprite) {
        global.dots_sprite.SetOpacity(0);
    }
    global.dialog_active = 0;
    title_sprite.SetOpacity(1);
    subtitle_sprite.SetOpacity(0.85);
}

Plymouth.SetDisplayNormalFunction(display_normal_callback);
